ive to that of his predecessor by creating a form of kingship for his hero which is more practicable than Wolfram's millennial 'Grail realm'. Rejecting the notion of an ideal space altogether, Wirnt's naturalistic descriptions ofhis hero's kingship give expression to a harmonisation of Arthurian and theocratic elements. The author thus suggests that Wigalois is not so much a paler imitation of Parzival as a creative confrontation with the thought-world of its more famous predecessor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aArthurian romance.  aGerman literature.  aIntertextuality.  aKing Arthur.  aKnightly existence.  aLiterary analysis.  aLiterary criticism.  aMedieval literature.  aSpiritual dimension.  aWigalois.  aWirnt von Gravenberg.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154362423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154362/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles